Data Visualization with Altair

Written by Oceane Andreis

"Altair is a visualization library for Python notable for taking a declarative approach based on a grammar of graphics using Vega and Vega-Lite. As Jake VanderPlas explains when presenting Altair, this allows visualization concepts to map directly to visualization implementation."

(Source: https://matthewkudija.com/blog/2018/06/22/altair-interactive/)

Data Visualization is truly an art. It's one with sets of rules. When you have data, you can tell a story, answer questions, and see trends. I played around with a very challenging dataset. It could be argued that it wasn't a good dataset. The data was mostly boolean and it made it complicated to do data visualization.

I'm using a mental health survey from kaggle. Kaggle is a very great website to learn data science and to grab dataset.

I first imported my dataset

import pandas as pd
import altair as alt
data = pd.read_csv("survey.csv") #Source: https://www.kaggle.com/osmi/mental-health-in-tech-survey
data.head()

I did 3 different visualizations to answer 3 different questions:

1. Bar graph

Question: Are people who have company benefits more likely to sought out treatment?

brush = alt.selection_interval()
base = alt.Chart(data).mark_bar().encode(
    y='Age',
    color=alt.condition(brush, 'Age', alt.ColorValue('gray')),
    tooltip = ["Age", "work_interfere_word", "benefits"],
).add_selection(
    brush
).properties(
    width=350,
    height=250
)
DataVis1Combined = base.encode(x='benefits:O') | base.encode(x='Gender') # Did this to export this as html
DataVis1Combined

2. Scatter Plot

Question: Does remote work affect mental health depending on if their employer provide resources?

alt.Chart(data).mark_circle().encode(
    x = "Age:N",
    y = "remote_work",
    size = 'mean(work_interfere)',
    tooltip = ["work_interfere_word", "seek_help"],
    color = "seek_help"
).properties(
    width=850,
    height=150
)

3. Line Graph

Question: Is it more taboo to talk about mental health than physical health?

# I had to sort my data so I could pick an age range and then only show the data from that age range using pandas

sorted_df = data.sort_values(by='Age')
mental_health = alt.Chart(sorted_df.iloc[4:1254,]).mark_trail().encode(
    x= alt.X('Age',scale=alt.Scale(domain=[18, 60])),
    y= 'mean(mental_health_consequence)'
)
physical_health = alt.Chart(sorted_df.iloc[5:1254,]).mark_trail().encode(
    x= alt.X('Age',scale=alt.Scale(domain=[18, 60])),
    y= 'mean(phys_health_consequence)'
)
DataVis3Combined = mental_health | physical_health # Did this to export this as html
DataVis3Combined
